<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ericameria</i> <i>teretifolia</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Artemisia</i> <i>ludoviciana</i>, <i>Cylindropuntia</i> <i>acanthocarpa</i>, <i>Ephedra</i> <i>viridis</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Grayia</i> <i>spinosa</i>, <i>Gutierrezia</i> <i>sarothrae</i>, <i>Opuntia</i> <i>chlorotica</i>, <i>Prunus</i> <i>fasciculata</i>, <i>Salazaria</i> <i>mexicana</i>, <i>Salvia</i> <i>dorrii</i> and <i>Sphaeralcea</i> <i>ambigua</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 2 m; canopy is intermittent to sparse. Herbaceous layer is open to intermittent and grassy. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Ericameria teretifolia</i> to other species (such as <i>Eriogonum fasciculatum, Guiterrezia sarothrae,</i> or <i>Opuntia chlorotica)</i> in relative cover in the shrub canopy (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b, Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Disturbed areas, including burns, washes, road cuts, and heavily grazed sites. Soils are variable in parent material and usually coarse, well drained, and moderately acidic to slightly saline.  </div>
</div>

        
