    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa, Ad, Af-h, Aj, Al, An-p). Stands are associated with <i>Pinus monophylla</i> and <i>Juniperus</i> sp. alliances in the higher elevations of the section. Stands are relatively few and large in the eastern and northern subsections (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dj). Stands are known from the White Mountains at mid elevations.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er). Stands are known from the eastern escarpment in the pinyon and juniper zone.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-f). Stands occur along road cuts in upper elevation portions of Death Valley National Park (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bi, Bp). Stands occur on the eastern slopes of the Transverse and Peninsular ranges in Anza-Borrego State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> This seral type is part of the natural matrix of mid-to-upper desert patterns, but large stands may indicate anthropogenic disturbance. </div>
</div>

    

    

